arch:property.oc:show_val: This is supposed to be fill with fresh material dumped in it from ca. Level IV, north of B. 44 in the South area. It is a moderate size unit with moderate fragmentation. Mostly sheep-size but with a goodly amount of large mammal. Diagnostics are more heavily sheep/goat, with a little bit of cattle and a very little dog. Very little burning, some digestion. Surface condition variable, with a few rather fresh, mostly somewhat worn. Not a lot of coherence. Sheep-size is fairly even through the body, but short on the toes, ribs, and vertebrae; a lot of sheep/goat teeth and mandibles/maxillae, most of them shattered beyond reconstruction. Does not really look middeny, but not like your typical fill, either. For the most part it looks like relatively slowly accumulating post-consumption waste, not as heavily processed as some. Does not look tremendously reworked. Note that there are at least five different right proximal sheep/goat metacarpals, i.e. MNI 5; but three of them are digested. Sample 2 >4mm flotation 100% sorted, recorded as diagnostics and flot frags only. It is a medium-large sample, mostly little crumbles of background noise. There are few diagnostics. Heavily sheep-size, a little burning, fair amount of digestion. Surface condition variable, tending to slightly worn but with some fresh pieces. Looks like fill; probably not catching much of the fresh dump portion here. Remarkably free of microfauna and fish.

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
